## Step 1 — Lessons from Similar Tasks

Write a short section: "Lessons Relevant to This Task"
- Check git history, `// TODO`, `// FIXME`, `// HACK` comments near the area
- Call out common AI mistakes for this task type (async edge cases, missing null guards, happy-path-only tests, etc.)

---

## Step 2 — Scenario Analysis

List ALL scenarios before writing a single test:
- **Happy path** — primary flow when everything works
- **Error path** — what can fail and what the system does for each
- **Edge cases** — empty/null/zero inputs, double-submit, race conditions, missing permissions, empty list vs thousands, etc.

---

## Step 3 — Test Strategy

Assign every scenario to the correct layer:
- **Unit** — pure functions, isolated components, hooks with all deps mocked
- **Integration** — component + hook + context together, only network boundary mocked (MSW)
- **E2E** — critical full-user journeys only

---

## Step 4 — Module & File Breakdown

For each file: purpose, exports, dependencies, side effects. Flag files touching >3 concerns.

---

## Step 5 — Execution Flow

Short prose description of the full flow from user action to system response.

---

## Step 6 — Approval Gate

**STOP. Present the full plan (Steps 1–5). Ask:**
> "Does this plan look right? Should I adjust anything before I start writing tests?"

Only proceed after the user explicitly approves.
